SIMPLE: tympan
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Tympan
<hw>Tym"pan</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. L.
<ets>tympanum</ets> a kettledrum, a panel of a door. See
<er>Tympanum</er>, and cf. <er>Tymp</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
drum.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>A panel; a tympanum.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Print.)</fld> <def>A frame covered with parchment
or cloth, on which the blank sheets are put, in order to be laid on the
form to be impressed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Tympan sheet</b></col> <fld>(Print.)</fld>, <cd>a sheet
of paper of the same size as that to be printed, pasted on the tympan,
and serving as a guide in laying the sheets evenly for printing.</cd>
<rj><au>W. Savage.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tympanal</ent>⟦br⟧
